HEADWORD: cede
<hw>cede</hw> <pr>(s⟦emac⟧d)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. &
p. p.</pos> <conjf>ceded</conjf>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>ceding</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[L. <ets>cedere</ets> to withdraw,
yield; akin to <ets>cadere</ets> to fall, and to E. <ets>chance</ets>;
cf. F. <ets>c⟦eacute⟧der</ets>.]</ety> <def>To yield or surrender; to
give up; to resign; <as>as, to <ex>cede</ex> a fortress, a province, or
country, to another nation, by treaty</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The people must <xex>cede</xex> to the government some of their
natural rights.</q> <rj><qau>Jay.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

